Favorsky Irkutsk Institute of Chemistry, Siberian Branch  of the Russian Academy of Sciences, 1 Favorsky St., Irkutsk  664033, Russian Federation boris_trofimov@irioch.irk.ru The 2-pyridone scaffold is frequently met in the struc- tures of many medicines, for example the phosphodiester- ase  3  inhibitors  milrinone  and  olprinone,  which  are  used for the treatment of congestive heart failure,1 topoisomer- ase I inhibitor, anticancer drug (+)-camptothecin,2 HIV re- verse transcriptase inhibitor pyridone L-697, 661,3 antiepi- leptic drug perampanel,4 antibiotic fredericamycin A,5 anti- fungal  agent  ciclopirox,6  and  various  molecules  exhibiting diverse biological activities including anticancer,7 antiviral,8 anti-inflammatory  and  analgesic,9  antifungal,10a  antibacte- rial10b,c and other properties (Figure 1). Besides, 2-pyridone derivatives  are  powerful  precursors  for  the  syntheses  of piperidine,  pyridine,  indolizidine  and  quinolizidine  alka- loids  and  alkaloid-inspired  compounds.11  It  is  also  known that among 2-pyridone derivatives, there are dyes12 and flu- orophores.13 They are also employed in the manufacture of dyes,  additives  for  fuels  and  lubricants,  acid–base  indica- tors, stabilizers for polymers and coatings.14

Although these properties have stimulated the develop- ment of a large number of synthetic methods to construct and  decorate  the  2-pyridone  moiety,15  there  is  still  an  ur- gent need for new 2-pyridone derivatives especially those having  biologically  active  counterparts,  in  particular,  the pyrrole  ring.  Such  pyrrole-pyridone  ensembles  remain  al- Received: 06.04.2020 Accepted after revision: 18.05.2020 Published online: 16.06.2020 DOI: 10.1055/s-0040-1707148; Art ID: ss-2020-t0184-op Abstract  An  efficient  synthesis  of  pharmacologically  oriented,  func- tionalized pyrrole-pyridone ensembles by the reaction of available acy- lethynylpyrroles  with  methylene  active  amides  in  almost  quantitative yields  has  been  implemented.  The  cyclocondensation  proceeds smoothly at room temperature in a KOH/DMSO superbase suspension. Key words  pyrrole-pyridones,  acylethynylpyrroles,  CH-acids,  metal- free cross-coupling © 2020. most  unknown.  The  few  exceptions  include  1-methylpyr- role linked with cyanopyridone, which can be considered as a prospective dual antitumor and antioxidant agent.16 This ensemble has been prepared via multicomponent, one-pot cyclocondensation of 1-methylpyrrole-2-carbaldehyde with the appropriate ketone, ethyl cyanoacetate and ammonium acetate as a nitrogen source. Unfortunately, this protocol is significantly  limited  to  only  one  pyrrole-2-carbaldehyde. However it could have a broader scope if, for its extension, the improved synthesis of differently substituted pyrrole-2- carbaldehydes was employed.17 One of the most straightforward approaches to pyrrole- pyridone ensembles could be the addition of methylene ac- tive  amides  to  acylethynylpyrroles,  now  readily  available due to the transition-metal-free cross-coupling of pyrroles with  acylhaloacetylenes  in  solid  metal  oxide  or  salt  me- dia.18 Both pyrroles19 and acylhaloacetylenes20 are also easi- ly accessible thanks to the existing robust methods for their preparation.  Along  this  line,  just  one  patent  discloses  the reaction  of  cyanoacetamide  with  pent-3-yn-2-one  in  the system t-BuOK/DMSO to give pyridone.21 However, as our studies  have  shown,  the  reaction  of  acylethynylpyrroles with  cyanoacetamide  under  these  conditions  leads  to resinification  of  the  reaction  mixture,  while  the  target products are not fixed. Figure 1   Drugs and agents containing a 2-pyridone moiety Perampanel (antiepileptic drug) R5 = CN, C(O)NH2 R6 = H, Me N Milrinone (vasodilator) Mild conditions Yield up to 98% Ciclopirox (antifungal agent)

. l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C Here,  we  report  the  experimental  features  concerning the  synthesis  of  pyrrole-pyridone  ensembles  via  the  reac- tion of 2-(acylethynyl)pyrroles 1a–k with methylene active amides 2a–c such as cyanoacetamides and malonodiamide. To begin with, we tested the possibility of a synthesis of these ensembles via the reaction of 2-(benzoylethynyl)-1H- pyrrole  (1a)  with  cyanoacetamide  (2a).  This  reaction  was performed by stirring a mixture of the reactants (molar ra- tio  1a/2a  =  1:1.5)  the  superbase  suspension KOH·0.5 H2O/DMSO  (1.5  equiv  of  KOH  relative  to  1a)  at room  temperature  for  24  hours  to  give  the  target  pyr- rolylpyridone 3a (Scheme 1). The reaction course was mon- itored by 1H NMR spectroscopy. After the disappearance of the signals of the starting pyrrole 1a in the  1H NMR spec- trum,  the  reaction  mixture  was  diluted  with  ice–water (1:1) and the formed precipitate was collected by filtration. However, the product was almost insoluble in common or- ganic solvents which hampered establishing its structure.

To overcome this problem, we alkylated compound 3a with  MeI  in  acetone  in  the  presence  of  K2CO3  (room  tem- perature, 24 h) to selectively afford O-alkylated pyrrolylpyr- idine 4a (Scheme 2). This is inconsistent with the published data  that  3-cyanopyridin-2-one  was  methylated  with  MeI in the presence of K2CO3 at the nitrogen atom.22 Methylation  (MeI,  room  temperature,  24  h)  of  pyr- rolylpyridone 3a in a KOH/DMSO system gave dimethylated derivative  5a  with  methyl  groups  located  in  the  pyrrole (NMe) and pyridine (OMe) rings (Scheme 2). Both the mo- no- and dimethylated derivatives, 4a and 5a, were well sol- uble in CDCl3 and their structures were reliably proved by NMR (1H and 13C) spectroscopy that allowed confirmation, in turn, of the structure of pyrrolylpyridone 3a. To check the substrate scope of this cyclization, we in- vestigated  the  reaction  of  a  variety  of  acylethynylpyrroles 1b–k with cyanoacetamide (2a) under the above conditions (Scheme 1). As follows from Scheme 3, a wide range of di- Scheme 1   Formation of pyrrolylpyridone 3a Scheme 2   Methylation of pyrrolylpyridone 3a © 2020. Thieme. All rights reserved. Synthesis 2020, 52, A–G versely substituted acylethynylpyrroles 1a–k were suitable substrates,  ensuring  the  synthesis  of  the  corresponding pyrrole-pyridone  ensembles  3a–k  in  near  to  quantitative isolated yields.

Formation of the pyridone ring starts by deprotonation of the cyanoacetamide CH2 group followed by nucleophilic addition of carbanion A, thus formed, to the triple bond of acylethynylpyrrole 1 to generate carbanion B, which is fur- ther quenched by a proton of the medium. The intermedi- ate  ethylenic  ketone  is  then  condensed  with  the  amide group  to  close  the  cycle  with  elimination  of  H2O  (Scheme 4). Isolated  yields. Scheme 4   Proposed mechanism of pyridone formation . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C Using  2-cyano-N-methylacetamide  (2b)  as  methylene active  amide  in  the  reaction  with  acylethynylpyrroles  1a and 1l, we prepared the corresponding N-methylated pyr- rolylpyridones  6a,b  in  92%  and  84%  yield,  respectively (Scheme 5). The reactions were carried out under the same conditions as above. Likewise, malonodiamide (2c) was employed for build- ing up the pyridone ring onto the acylethynylpyrrole plat- form.  However,  contrary  to  the  expectations,  the  reaction products in this case were pyrrolylpyridones 7a,b without a carbamoyl group (Scheme 6).

Further, we used cyanothioacetamide (2d) as an activat- ed amide compound in a reaction with acylethynylpyrrole 1f. Interestingly, this interaction ended with the formation of  only  enethiol  8  in  a  yield  of  78%  (Scheme  7).  This  con- trasts  with  the  fact  that  cyanothioacetamide  reacts  with readily available23 ,-acetylenic ketones in the presence of a base to give 3-cyanopyridine-2-thiones.24 Probably, in our case, cyanothioacetamide reacts as its thiol tautomer with the triple bond of 1f to deliver interme- diate A, which is further hydrolyzed to thiol 8 (Scheme 8). А  similar  result  could  be  explained  by  the  addition  of H2S,  resulting  from  dimerization  of  cyanothioacetamide, described in the literature.24 However, as our studies have shown,  cyanothioacetamide  in  the  KOH/DMSO  system  is Scheme 5   Reaction of acylethynylpyrroles 1a,l with 2-cyano-N-methyl- acetamide (2b). Reagents and conditions: 1 (1 mmol), 2b (1.5 mmol),  KOH (1.5 mmol), DMSO (10.0 mL), rt, 24 h. Isolated yields. Scheme 6   Reaction of acylethynylpyrroles 1d,f with malonodiamide  (2c). Reagents and conditions: 1 (1 mmol), 2c (1.5 mmol), KOH (1.5  mmol), DMSO (10.0 mL), rt, 24 h. Isolated yields. © 2020. Thieme. All rights reserved. Synthesis 2020, 52, A–G

stable and can be recovered completely from the mixture. In  addition,  it  was  established  that  H2S  with  acylethynyl- pyrrole  1f  under  the  indicated  conditions  does  not  form enethiol 8. In  conclusion,  we  have  developed  a  high-yield,  room temperature  synthesis  of  medicinally  related,  functional- ized  pyrrole-pyridone  ensembles  via  the  superbase-cata- lyzed (KOH/DMSO) cyclocondensation of methylene active amides  to  available  acylethynylpyrroles.  The  biomimetic, transition-metal-free  conditions  of  the  synthesis  with  its mostly  atom-economic,  one-pot  character  meets  the  re- quirements  of  a  pot-,  atom-  and  step-economic  (PASE)25 paradigm. In combination with highly thought-out synthe- sized  heterocyclic  compounds,  this  synthetic  strategy  will likely  activate  the  interest  of  both  synthetic  and  pharma- ceutical communities.

A  suspension  of  cyanothioacetamide  (2d;  150  mg,  1.5  mmol)  and KOH (98 mg, 1.75 mmol) in DMSO (5 mL) was stirred at 20–25 °C for 30 min. Then, a solution of acylethynylpyrrole 1f (263 mg, 1 mmol) in DMSO (5 mL) was added dropwise to the mixture within 10 min. The reaction mixture was stirred at 20–25 °C for 24 h. After reaction com- pletion, the reaction mixture was diluted with H2O (40 mL) and ex- tracted  with  Et2O  (5 × 30  mL).  The  extracts  were  washed  with  H2O and dried over K2CO3. The residue, after removal of solvent, afforded target enethiol 8; yield: 232 mg (78%); yellow oil.
